# verasic-jsdoc-and-comments

Portable Verasic rule — copy to `.cursor/rules/verasic-jsdoc-and-comments.mdc` in any repo. Pair with `verasic-git-commits.mdc` (same casing for commits).

**Optional `AGENTS.md` row:**

```markdown
| JSDoc / code comments | [.cursor/rules/verasic-jsdoc-and-comments.mdc](.cursor/rules/verasic-jsdoc-and-comments.mdc) |
```

**Optional long-form spec:** some repos add `docs/conventions/jsdoc-and-comments.md` and link it from `AGENTS.md`. This rule is enough on its own; the doc is supplementary.

Applies to **block comments, JSDoc, and inline comments in source files** — not markdown docs, not commit messages (see `verasic-git-commits.mdc`).

Adjust **`globs`** in the frontmatter to match your source roots (`app/`, `src/`, `packages/*/src/`, etc.).

## Casing

- lowercase first sentence (and after `.`, `?`, `!`, `;`, `:`, `—`)
- natural casing for types, acronyms, API routes, component names, field labels (`User ID`, `BRANCH`, `PROJ-1234`)
- inline code (backticks) for technical literals when helpful — same idea as `verasic-git-commits.mdc`: CLI flags (`--dry-run`), paths (`src/utils/foo.ts`), commands (`npm run test`)

## JSDoc content

- explain **intent and data flow** — types stay in TypeScript; do not duplicate `@param` / `@returns` types unless the name alone is unclear
- inline comments: **why**, not what the code already says
- skip JSDoc on obvious getters/setters and self-describing one-liners

## `@example` count

| Complexity                                                                      | Count   |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------- |
| very simple (unary / obvious args → output)                                     | **1**   |
| more than very simple (payload mappers, nested shapes, branching, store wiring) | **≥ 2** |

## `@example` format

**Very simple** — real call, then `=>` result on the next line:

```typescript
/**
 * format user display name for list cells.
 *
 * @example
 * formatDisplayName('  alice  ')
 * => 'Alice'
 */
```

**More than very simple** — optional `// input:` sketch, real call(s), `=>` result shape. Always use the **real function name**:

```typescript
/**
 * map API row to table column value.
 *
 * @example
 * // input: { status: 'ACTIVE', branch_code: 'JKT' }
 * mapRowStatus({ status: 'ACTIVE', branch_code: 'JKT' })
 * => 'Active · JKT'
 *
 * @example
 * mapRowStatus({ status: undefined, branch_code: '' })
 * => '-'
 */
```

## When to document

| Sit                                        | Action                                                                |
| ------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| exported util, hook, mapper, store action  | JSDoc + `@example` per count rule                                     |
| internal helper, obvious from name + types | inline **why** only if non-obvious                                    |
| React component props (public/shared)      | brief file or props block comment if behavior is not obvious from JSX |
| generated or trivial pass-through          | skip                                                                  |

## PR checklist (comments only)

- first sentence lowercase; acronyms/types natural casing
- no `@param` type duplication when TS already types it
- `@example` count matches complexity; examples use real symbols and plausible values
- commit message for the same change follows `verasic-git-commits.mdc`

## Repo-specific overlays

Team or initiative docs may add stricter rules (e.g. mandatory `@example` on all exports). Keep those in the initiative doc; do not fork Verasic casing defaults per repo unless the team explicitly changes them.
